{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2ab56c76-1a2c-45f1-92be-f562023e7094","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **abstract file I/O behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen inject `IFileSystem` into classes that need it. In production, wire up a thin implementation that delegates to `System.IO`. In tests, use a mock or an in-memory fake.\n\n**Alternatives:**\n\n- **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — popular NuGet package that provides `IFileSystem` out of the box, plus a `MockFileSystem` for tests.\n- **`Microsoft.Extensions.FileProviders`** — useful for read-only scenarios.\n\n`System.IO.Abstractions` is the lowest-friction option if you don't want to maintain your own interface:\n\n```csharp\n// Production\nservices.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();\n\n// Tests\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem();\nfs.AddFile(\"/data/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{}\"));\nvar sut = new MyService(fs);\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Wrap file system calls behind an interface, inject it, and swap in a fake/mock during tests. Use `System.IO.Abstractions` to avoid boilerplate.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2e09baea-4a71-4db8-a6cf-73d31137c2ed","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations (`File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) testable in their .NET project. This is a common software design question about dependency injection and abstraction.\n\nLet me give a concise answer about the best practices for making file system calls testable in .NET.","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"BC3A:1129F2:1F6047C:22C1A4F:69FA9BCA"},"id":"f19c3941-078a-4230-9e1a-c47a04924e61","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:39:31.640Z","parentId":"c908bb1d-91aa-450c-9e7d-20013e236b1f"}
